MUMPS - USA (NEBRASKA, IOWA) (05)
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Fri 14 Apr 2006
From: George Robertson <GRobertson@neotropix.com>
Source: washingtonpost.com, Thu 13 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/04/12/AR2006041201458.html>

Health officials are battling a mumps epidemic in the Midwest that
has infected at least 515 individuals in Iowa, mostly young adults,
and spread from Iowa to a number of other states. At least 100 cases
of mumps have also been recorded in nearby Nebraska, Kansas,
Minnesota, Wisconsin, Indiana, Michigan, Missouri, and Illinois.
Investigators are following leads to the United Kingdom, which
because of relatively low vaccine uptake rates due to fears over
links to autism has been battling mumps outbreaks for years; the
mumps strain seen in Iowa is the same as the one in the United
Kingdom.
The number of cases experienced in the epidemic this year, the
largest since a 1988 outbreak in Kansas, far outpaces the 200 to 300
typically experienced in the United States annually. Health officials
are responding with vaccine campaigns and investigating the
possibility that the protection afforded by the vaccine being used
wanes over time, or is simply not as strong as thought. Nearly 70
percent of the infected individuals had received the 2 recommended
doses of the mumps vaccine as part of routine childhood immunization
schedules. The vaccine is believed to be 95 percent effective.
--
