[Mumps infection occurs worldwide, and humans are the only natural
host for the virus. The virus is essentially monotypic, although
there may some mismatch between individual strains and vaccines.
Despite the monotypic nature of mumps virus, different genetic
lineages of mumps virus exist and co-circulate globally. Genotypes A
to J have been defined on the basis of the nucleotide sequence of the
most variable gene, the SH gene. Previously state health officials
have stated that they are concerned that a rare genotype of mumps
virus may be responsible for this unusually large outbreak of mumps
in midwestern states. The strain of mumps virus implicated in this
outbreak is a genotype G strain, a genotype that has been seen
infrequently in the United States. It has been suggested that the
virus may have been imported from the United Kingdom or Ireland where
there have been extensive outbreaks of mumps in recent years.
However, a similar strain has been isolated also in New Jersey,
and the Centers for Disease Control have yet to make a pronouncement
on the suspected origin of the epidemic strain. - Mod.CP]
